SATIRE XI.

--This Satire consists principally of an invitation to Persicus, the poet’s friend, to-spend the day with him3 in the course of which, he takes occasion to expose and reprehend in the severest terms' all manner of 'intemperance and debauchery 3 but, more particularly, the luxury, used by the Romans, at their feasts.

1. Atticus t the name is here used for any person of great wealth. 2. Rutilus : used here for any person, who, by extravagant gluttony, has been reduced to poverty.
